tion period; the Jim Crow era, when competition between the parties virtually disappeared; and the modern era-Aldrich and Griffin show how and when competition emerged between the parties and the conditions under which it succeeded and failed. In the modern era, as party competition in the South has come to be widely regarded as matching that of the North, the authors conclude by exploring the question of whether the South is poised to become a one-party system once again with the Republican party now dominant.    aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 22. Okt 2019) 0aDemocracyzSouthern StatesxHistory. 0aElectionszSouthern StatesxHistory. 0aPolitical partieszSouthern StatesxHistory. 4acompetition. 4ademocracy. 4ahistory. 4aparties. 4arepresentation. 4asouth. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / General.2bisacsh1 aGriffin, John D., eauthor.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018z978311063537940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226495408423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780226495408.jpg  a978-3-11-063537-9  University of Chicago Press eBook Package 2016-2018c2016d2018  aGBV-deGruyter-alles